Inheritance
-----------

One class can use the properties and methods of another class.

It helps in:
    -Code reuse
    -Reducing duplication
    -Creating hierarchy

Inheritance represents IS-A.

Child class inherits:
    ✔ Public methods
    ✔ Protected methods
    ✔ Non-private variables

Child class does NOT inherit:
    ❌ Private members (they exist but cannot be accessed directly). They can only be accessed through public or protected methods of the parent.

            class Parent {
                private int x = 10;

                public int getX() {
                    return x;
                }
            }

            class Child extends Parent {
                void display() {
                    System.out.println(getX());  // ✅ Allowed
                }
            }

Memory is created for a Child object. Since Child extends Parent, the Parent part is also created inside the Child object.
So the Child object contains:
    -Parent properties & methods
    -Child properties & methods

If a child class doesn’t override a method, it uses the parent’s version.

When child method is called, JVM uses dynamic method lookup.
It first checks in Child class, and if not found, it checks Parent class and executes the method from there.

Why Java doesn’t allow multiple inheritance (very important interview question)
Because of the Diamond Problem: JVM wouldn’t know which method to call, causes ambiguity.
Java allows multiple inheritance only through interfaces.
